data.content:
Each file hits a different C# 13 breaking change. Here's what breaks and the fixes:

---

**1. Buffer.cs** — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` is now prohibited ([spec change](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/whats-new/breaking-changes/compiler%20breaking%20changes%20-%20dotnet%209#inline-array-struct)).

The `record` synthesizes `Equals`/`GetHashCode`/`ToString` that conflict with inline-array semantics. Fix: use a plain `struct`.

```csharp
[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]
struct Buffer
{
    private int _element0;
}
```

---

**2. Generator.cs** — C# 13 now permits `unsafe` contexts inside iterator methods, but as a consequence, `stackalloc` inside a local function of an iterator is now treated as part of the iterator state machine and is disallowed.

Fix: extract the local function to a regular `static` method so it's outside the iterator's scope.

```csharp
unsafe class DataGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<int> Generate()
    {
        yield return 1;
        Process();
    }

    static void Process()
    {
        int* p = stackalloc int[10];
        // ... work with pointer
    }
}
```

---

**3. Resolver.cs** — C# 13 adds first-class `Span` conversions, so `[]` now matches **both** overloads (`ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`), causing an ambiguity error.

Fix: disambiguate with an explicit type on the collection expression.

```csharp
class Resolver
{
    static void Process(ReadOnlySpan<int> ros) {}
    static void Process(Span<object> s) {}

    static void Main()
    {
        Process(ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty);
        // or: Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);
    }
}
```

---

**Summary**

| File | Breaking change | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Buffer.cs | `[InlineArray]` banned on `record struct` | Change to plain `struct` |
| Generator.cs | `stackalloc` in iterator local functions disallowed | Extract to a separate `static` method |
| Resolver.cs | New `Span` conversions cause overload ambiguity | Explicitly specify the target type |
